Headline: : Elron to Host Fourth Quarter and Year End 2006 Earnings Conference Call on Wednesday, March 14, 2007
Story: TEL AVIV, Israel--(BUSINESS WIRE)--March 11, 2007--   Elron Electronic Industries Ltd. (NASDAQ: ELRN, TASE: ELRN) today announced that it will be hosting a conference call on Wednesday, March 14, 2007 at 10:00am ET and 4.00pm Israel time to discuss its fourth quarter and full year 2006 results. The company plans to release its results on Wednesday, March 14th, 2007.     To participate, please call one of the following teleconferencing numbers. Please begin placing your calls at least 10 minutes before the conference call commences. If you are unable to connect using the toll-free numbers, please try the international dial-in number.                        In the US:     1 888 668 9141                      In the UK:     0 800 051 8913                      In Israel:     03 918 0650                      International Participants: +972 3 918 0650                                     at:                 10:00am Eastern Time, 7:00am Pacific Time,                      2:00pm GMT and 4:00pm Israel Time     For your convenience, a replay of the call will be available starting three hours after the call ends until Friday, March 16th, 2007. The replay numbers are: 1 888 782 4291 (US); 0 800 028 6837 (UK) and +972 3 925 5927 (International).     A replay of the call will also be available for ninety days on the company website.     Elron Electronic Industries Ltd., a member of the IDB Holding group, is a leading Israel-based technology holding company directly involved in the long-term performance of its group companies. Elron identifies potential technologies, creates strategic partnerships, secures financing, and recruits senior management teams. Elron's group companies currently comprise a diverse range of publicly-traded and privately held companies primarily in the fields of medical devices, information & communications technology, semiconductors and clean technology. For further information, please visit www.elron.com       (Any statements in this press release that may be considered  forward-looking statements are subject to risks and uncertainties that  could cause actual results to differ materially. Actual results may  differ from such forward-looking statements due to the risk factors  discussed in periodic reports filed by the Company with the Securities  and Exchange Commission, which the Company urges investors to  consider.) Headline: Ford To Keep 15% Aston Martin Stake After Sale - Newspapers
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Ford Motor Co. (F) is to keep a stake of around 15% in Aston Martin when it sells the luxury division to a consortium this week, two U.K. newspapers say Sunday.   Ford put the business up for sale last year as part of a restructuring of its North American and European operations.   The Sunday Times and Sunday Telegraph say the sale will value the unit at around GBP450 million. The newspapers say it is being sold to Prodrive, a motor-racing and specialist engineering company founded by motor industry entrepreneur David Richards, with the backing of a group of investors from the Middle East.   The Sunday Telegraph says Ford will continue to provide technical support and components to the company.   Ford and Aston Martin couldn't immediately be reached to comment.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.co.uk   Newspaper Web site: http://www.telegraph.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 09:24 ET (13:24 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : Synenco Energy Releases 2006 Results>SYN.T
Story: CALGARY, March 9 /CNW/ - Synenco Energy Inc. (TSX: SYN) today released financial results and operating highlights for the year ended December 31, 2006.    Synenco reported net income for the year ended December 31, 2006 of $3.9 million ($0.07 per diluted share) compared to a net loss of $5.9 million ($0.22 per share) in 2005. Net income was higher in 2006 as a result of increased interest income due to the larger cash investment balance maintained throughout the year. The higher 2006 interest income was partially offset by increased office and corporate costs related to Synenco's corporate build-out activity.    Most costs incurred relate to the Northern Lights Partnership (NLP) project development activities and are capitalized. As a development stage entity, Synenco expects it will report net losses in most periods until project development activities are complete and operations commence.    Synenco also reported consolidated capital expenditures of $109.6 million for the year ended December 31, 2006. The consolidated capital expenditures include amounts incurred by the Northern Lights Partnership, in which Synenco's equity participation is 60%. Synenco's net ownership interest in consolidated capital expenditures was $71.1 million. Capital expenditures in the year are mainly comprised of drilling activities, engineering-related activities, technology-licensing costs, work on the Environmental Impact Assessments to support the regulatory applications for the Northern Lights project and capitalized corporate and personnel costs.    Cash expenditures in 2006 amounted to $78 million compared to the announced 2006 budget of $118 million, in both cases net to Synenco's ownership interest in NLP. At the end of 2006, Synenco's consolidated cash and cash equivalents were $406.8 million including NLP funds. Synenco's share of the total consolidated cash and cash equivalents available to meet its future obligations was $342.7 million. Synenco also reported positive consolidated working capital of $386.4 million at December 31, 2006. Synenco's share of total consolidated working capital available at December 31, 2006 was $329.3 million.    A summary of Synenco's consolidated financial results as at and for the years ended December 31, 2006 and 2005 is included below:          <<      Selected Financial Information      (In thousands except per share data)      -------------------------------------------------------------------------      For the years ended December 31,                      2006          2005      -------------------------------------------------------------------------      Interest income                                     16,503         3,324      Personnel costs, net of amounts capitalized          4,454         4,401      Stock-based compensation                             1,338         1,714      Financing costs                                          -           817      Office, corporate and other costs                    6,469         3,045      Income tax expense (recovery)                          342          (781)      Net income (loss)                                    3,900        (5,872)      Net income (loss) per share        Basic                                               0.08         (0.22)        Diluted                                             0.07         (0.22)      Total assets                                       670,346       577,986      Shareholders' equity                               439,437       424,843      Common shares outstanding                           50,251        48,013      -------------------------------------------------------------------------      >>      2006 operating highlights    In the fourth quarter, the company received updated independent resource estimates for the Northern Lights oil sands leases; that reflected an increase in the best estimate of discovered resource of 12 percent to 1.673 billion barrels (Synenco share 60 percent).    During 2006, engineering and development work advanced in respect of both upstream and downstream.          <<      -   In December, Synenco announced an updated capital cost estimate and          its overseas construction strategy for Northern Lights upstream          (mining and extraction). The capital cost was estimated in 2006          dollars at $4.4 billion (Synenco share: $2.6 billion) in relation to          production of 114,500 barrels per day of bitumen for 30 years. The          capital cost estimate reflects anticipated savings from the announced          construction strategy of $1.2 billion (Synenco share: $0.7 billion).          Synenco announced that new downstream guidance would be available in          2007.        -   In November, Synenco completed the sequenced filing with the Alberta          Energy and Utilities Board and Alberta Environment for the upstream          regulatory application, which included the final environmental          effects assessments on behalf of NLP. On January 10, 2007, Alberta          Environment advised that the application was deemed administratively          complete.        -   In September, Synenco Energy filed an application with the Alberta          Energy and Utilities Board and Alberta Environment to construct and          operate an upgrader in Sturgeon County, Alberta on behalf of NLP. On          October 12, 2006, Alberta Environment advised that the application          was deemed administratively complete.        -   In August, Synenco Energy announced the conversion of NLP's northern          permit to a primary oil sands lease with a 15-year term.        -   In July, Synenco Energy signed a Memorandum of Understanding with          Agrium for the supply of hydrogen, nitrogen, sulphur and carbon          dioxide from the upgrader to Agrium's neighbouring Redwater nitrogen          fertilizer operations on behalf of NLP.        -   In July, Synenco Energy signed two significant technology licensing          agreements on behalf of NLP:            -  An agreement with UOP Management Services Inc. to use its             Unicracking(TM) and RCD Unionfining(TM) technologies. Using these             technologies, the Northern Lights upgrader will be able to produce             a high quality synthetic crude oil or a lighter diluent product             for use in the transportation of bitumen.            -  An agreement with Kellogg Brown & Root International Inc. to use             its ROSE(TM) solvent de-asphalting technology that removes             asphaltenes from bitumen during the upgrading process. In the             Northern Lights configuration, the asphaltenes will be converted             to hydrogen in a separately licensed gasification process.        -   In June, Synenco Energy announced a licensing agreement with          GE Energy to use GE's gasification technology with the NLP upgrader.          The gasification of asphaltenes uses materials that would otherwise          be a waste product (requiring on-site storage and disposal) and is          anticipated to reduce the downstream project's reliance on external          energy purchases.        -   Also in June, Synenco Energy filed on behalf of NLP the first portion          of the sequenced upstream regulatory application with the Alberta          Energy and Utilities Board and Alberta Environment.        -   Earlier in June, Synenco Energy announced that NLP had retained          Citibank as the partnership's debt capitalization advisor to explore          global sources of project financing, evaluate various structures and          plan for debt capitalization that properly leverage both partners'          equity.        -   In May, Synenco announced the signing of a contract with          Jacobs Canada Inc. for NLP engineering services for the upgrader.        -   In April, Synenco announced an agreement with the joint venture of          Colt Engineering Corporation and AMEC Americas Limited for          engineering services related to NLP bitumen production. Under this          contract, Colt and AMEC developed the overall diagrams and plans          related to the bitumen extraction and froth treatment components of          the upstream project.        -   In March, Synenco announced contracts with: Jacobs Canada Inc. to          provide owner's engineering services; UMA Engineering Ltd. to provide          owner's engineering for on-lease and off-lease infrastructure; UMA to          complete the infrastructure DBM for the Northern Lights project; and          the consortium of UMA and Black & Veatch Canada Company, in respect          of the utilities and offsites DBM work.      >>      About Synenco Energy    Synenco Energy is a Calgary-based oil sands company, which, with a 60-percent interest, is the managing partner of the Northern Lights Partnership and operator of the Northern Lights project. (SinoCanada Petroleum Corporation, an indirect wholly owned subsidiary of China-based Sinopec, owns the remaining 40% of the partnership and project.) Synenco Energy also holds a 100-percent interest in the McClelland oil sands lease adjacent to the Northern Lights project lands. Visit Synenco's Web site at www.synenco.com.    About Northern Lights    The Northern Lights project consists of a planned oil sands mining and bitumen extraction project about 100 kilometres northeast of Fort McMurray, Alberta, and a planned heavy oil upgrader project in Sturgeon County near Edmonton. The project is designed to produce 100,000 barrels per day of synthetic crude oil for an estimated 30 years. Separate regulatory applications for each segment of the project were filed with the Alberta Energy and Utilities Board and Alberta Environment during 2006. The Northern Lights Partnership also holds extensive coal lease applications in the Athabasca region in northeastern Alberta.    Conference call    Synenco Energy will host a conference call to discuss 2006 results and provide a brief corporate update.          <<      Date:     March 12, 2007      Time:     9:00 a.m. Mountain (11:00 a.m. Eastern) Note: Daylight savings                time begins March 11.     (MORE TO FOLLOW) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 10:13 ET (14:13 GMT)

Headline: Colombian Political Scandal Could Affect US Aid Program
Story: By Deb Riechmann   Of THE ASSOCIATED PRESS   MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP)--A political scandal involving Colombian President Alvaro Uribe is making it difficult for President George W. Bush to convince the U.S. Congress that one of his best friends in Latin America is worthy of getting the largest slice of U.S. aid to the region.   Three days before Bush's visit Sunday, Uribe pleaded with the U.S. to continue a $700 million annual aid package that he says has helped stem the violence, corruption and drug trafficking that finance anti-government guerrillas.   "I ask the world, I ask the United States, to support us. We haven't yet won but we are winning. And we will persist," Uribe told The Associated Press.   Democrats in the U.S., who control the Congress, are wondering how well the mostly military aid to Colombia is working. Some want more of the money to go to social programs, or suggest it might be better spent to help the nation strengthen its own team of prosecutors.   Over the past seven years, the U.S. has sent $4 billion to Colombia to combat the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. The 15,000-strong peasant army, backed with drug profits, is on the U.S. list of terrorist groups.   "I look forward to telling President Uribe that he can count on the United States defending that which we sent up to Congress," Bush told foreign journalists before beginning a five-country tour of Latin America.   Lawmakers also are following developments in the political scandal in which eight of Uribe's close allies in Colombia's Congress and his hand-picked former domestic intelligence chief have been jailed recently for allegedly colluding with paramilitary groups.   "President Uribe has made it very clear that he is going to - he promotes and expects there to be a full investigation of any allegations," Bush said.   Bush said Uribe's pledge to fully prosecute wrongdoing shows he is a strong leader.   "I believe that that leadership will stand him in good stead with our Congress," Bush said.   Bush is less confident about a pending trade deal with Colombia that still needs lawmakers' approval.   "These are tough votes," he said.   Presidents have visited Colombia in recent years, but this will be the first time a U.S. president has stepped foot in the capital since President Reagan came in 1982. About 20,000 police and heavily armed troops will virtually shut off downtown Bogota to guard against a possible rebel attack.   On another issue of importance to both leaders, the U.S. embassy confirmed Saturday that U.S. and Colombian soldiers had conducted a joint operation in the southern stronghold of leftist rebels who are holding three U.S. military contractors.   The confirmation followed a report in Colombia's largest newspaper, citing unidentified sources, that two local residents had been detained in the late January operation and interrogated about the contractors' whereabouts.   "U.S. personnel accompanied Colombian forces in the south and that's all I can say about it," said U.S. Embassy spokesman Marshall Louis.   The three employees of Northrop Grumman Corp. (NOC), a large U.S. defense contractor, were captured by FARC in February 2003 when their surveillance plane went down.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 05:04 ET (09:04 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Warner Music To Sweeten EMI Offer, Sources Say - Newspaper
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Warner Music Group (WMG) Chairman Edgar Bronfman is ready to return with another bid for EMI Group PLC (EMI.LN), The Observer newspaper reports Sunday, citing Wall Street sources.   The newspaper said Bronfman is prepared to sweeten his offer for the U.K. music company but has to at least get the nod from EMI that a deal is possible.   A spokesman for Warner Music Group declined to comment.   On March 2 EMI said it had received and rejected a non-binding proposal from Warner Music Group at 260 pence a share.   It said the proposal "wasn't in the best interest of its shareholders and undervalues the company," and would lead to prolonged regulatory uncertainty and unacceptable operational risk at a critical time for the company.   The two companies previously had been in discussions last summer, but bid talks ended abruptly when a European Union court overturned clearance to another record company merger between parts of Sony Corp. (SNE) and Bertelsmann AG.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.observer.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 09:11 ET (13:11 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: 2nd UPDATE: NZ Warehouse Eyes Coles Assets, Seen As Good Fit
Story: (This story first ran Friday)         By Rachel Pannett and Susan Murdoch     Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     WELLINGTON (Dow Jones)--The Warehouse Group Ltd. (WHS.NZ) chief executive Ian Morrice Friday said the discount retailer may be interested in acquiring some of the assets of Australia's Coles Group Ltd. (CGJ.AU).   The move could see New Zealand's largest listed retailer reenter a market it quit in difficult circumstances in November 2005 following the sale of its loss-making Warehouse Australia division.   Morrice told Dow Jones Newswires in an interview that Warehouse is interested in Coles' Target discount department stores and Officeworks, a network of business supply stores. Both are potentially up for sale as part of an impending A$18.6 billion-plus (US$14.5 billion) breakup of Australia's second largest retailer.   "We would certainly be interested in Australia again for the right business," Morrice said. "We'll obviously wait and see what develops and see whether or not a bid is viable and a timely move to make," he said.    Warehouse has the balance sheet strength to bid for the businesses, Morrice said, noting that a bid of more than NZ$1 billion "wouldn't be a big challenge".   "We think there are a couple of businesses within Coles that are very complementary to the Warehouse setup in New Zealand," he said, tagging Target and Officeworks as strong businesses with great management.   Investment bank UBS has valued Target at A$3.9 billion, Officeworks at A$1.4 billion and Coles' discount department store Kmart at A$933 million.   Morrice's comments come at a time when Warehouse is itself in play, with rival supermarkets Australia-based Woolworths Ltd. (WOW.AU) and privately-owned Foodstuffs Ltd. seeking regulatory approval to mount bids.   They took defensive 10% stakes in Warehouse last year in response to its fledgling move into perishable groceries, with the New Zealand Commerce Commission to rule on the matter later this month.   "The appeal of Warehouse is the unique sites, 85 stores throughout New Zealand, unmatched in New Zealand and unable to be replicated through greenfields rollout," said Macquarie analyst Warren Doak.   Woolworths is also considered likely to be interested in Target, although it has declined comment. Australia-based furniture and electrical retailer Harvey Norman Holdings Ltd. (HVN.AU) has said it may look at buying Officeworks.   "Both those two businesses will be subject to an enormous amount of competition," said another analyst at major brokerage who declined to be named.   "There's speculation mid-tier private equity firms are very interested. There's a lot people with very deep pockets across the board."   Coles has said it expects the sale process to take three to six months.   One or two private equity consortiums, variously including global buyout giants such as Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co, Carlyle Group, Texas Pacific Group and Europe's Permira are expected to lodge bids for Coles.   A A$15.25 a share offer from a KKR-led consortium in late 2006 was rejected by Coles as inadequate and not put to shareholders. Coles shares ended Friday trade at A$15.72, valuing the company at about A$18.8 billion, while Warehouse shares gained 1.2%, spurred by the possible interest in Coles assets.   Warehouse appears to have put problems arising from its Australian foray behind it, Friday reporting an interim net profit of NZ$61 million compared with a NZ$7.96 million loss a year earlier.     -By Rachel Pannett, Dow Jones Newswires; 64-4-471-5990; rachel.pannett@dowjones.com     -Edited by Ian Pemberton     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 16:24 ET (20:24 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Banco Popolare Aims To Become Leader In Consumer Credit Ops
Story: MILAN (Dow Jones)--Banco Popolare SCARL aims to become the market leader in Italy's consumer credit business and is working on a merger of equals between Banca Popolare Italiana SCARL (BPI.MI) consumer credit unit Ducato SpA and its Italian peers Linea SpA and Delta Spa, Popolare Italiana director general Franco Baronio said Saturday.   "We are in advanced talks with all the shareholders of Linea and Delta and hope to sign a merger agreement in the next months," Baronio said. "Soon after the merger the new entity will be listed."   Banco Popolare, Italy's third largest bank by number of branches, is the results of a merger between Italian mutual banks Banca Popolare Verona e Novara SCARL (BPVN.MI) and Popolare Italiana. The merger will be effective July 1.   Popolare Verona e Novara controls a 48% stake in Linea and a 20% stake in Delta, Popolare Italiana owns 100% Ducato.   Observers believe Banco Popolare consumer credit unit is an undervalued asset.     -By Sabrina Cohen, Dow Jones Newswires, +39 347 3563 463; sabrina.cohen@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 08:39 ET (12:39 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Stop & Shop Union Members To Vote On Contract Offer Sunday
Story: BOSTON (AP)--Union locals representing 43,000 Stop & Shop supermarket workers in southern New England are scheduled to vote Sunday on the company's contract offer.   Stop & Shop spokesman Robert Keane said negotiations ended last night. He said the unions will take results of the talks to its members in meetings scheduled in Massachusetts, Rhode Island and Connecticut.   Workers on Sunday could vote to reject the contract and strike, though it's unclear when one would begin.   Keane won't comment on contract details until the union members have seen them. Union officials haven't returned messages left by The Associated Press.   Negotiations between the Quincy-based grocery chain and the United Food and Commercial Workers had stalled over issues including health care contributions, pensions and wages.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 08:45 ET (12:45 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Kuwait Firms Agree Buying Aston Martin Stake - Agencies
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Adeem Investment KSC and Investment Dar Co., two Kuwait-based Islamic investment companies, have joined former rally champion David Richards to bid for Ford Motor Co.'s (F) Aston Martin unit, the Bloomberg news agency reports Sunday, citing Adeem Chief Executive Mustafa al-Saleh.   It quotes Adeem Chief Executive Mustafa al-Saleh as saying "yes, it's true,"  when asked if the two Gulf companies have signed up with Richards' Prodrive Ltd. in an offer to buy Aston Martin from Ford Motor Co. (F).   The Reuters news agency Sunday cites an unnamed source as confirming a report in Kuwait's Al-Qabas newspaper that Investment Dar, Kuwait's largest diversified holding company, is leading a group of companies to buy a 15-20% stake in Aston Martin for about GBP400 million.   Reuters says Adeem Investment and Investment Dar will hold a press conference in London Monday at 0900 GMT to give more details about the agreement.   Neither Adeem Investment or Investment Dar were available for comment.     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 12:57 ET (16:57 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Alliance Boots Board To Meet "As Soon As Practicable"
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Alliance Boots PLC's (AB.LN) board is to meet as soon as is practicable to discuss a potential 1000 pence a share offer, a spokesman said Sunday.   Several U.K. newspapers said the board would meet Sunday or Monday to decide whether the company will open its books to private equity group Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. and Alliance Boots Executive Deputy Chairman Stefano Pessina, who Friday said they had made a friendly takeover approach valuing Alliance Boots at GBP9.67 billion.   The Sunday Telegraph and the Sunday Express, citing unnamed people close to the company, say the board is likely to support the potential bid but may hold out for a higher price.   "The board hasn't met yet, so any views on what they've decided is pure speculation, the Alliance Boots spokesman said.   He added board members would follow best corporate governance practices by not discussing the bid with each other or with involved parties such as Pessina or KKR executives.   Meanwhile, The Observer says at least one fund manager has contacted U.K. markets watchdog the Financial Services Authority about his concerns on a jump in Alliance Boots' share price before the company's statement Friday.   Shares in the company had risen sharply earlier in Friday's session, but analysts and traders had at the time dismissed the rise as purely due to "Friday talk".   Following the company's announcement, the shares closed Friday up 14%, or 115 pence, at 930 pence.   Last week, the FSA said it had found there was possible insider trading before one-quarter of takeover announcements in 2005.   Company Web site: http://www.allianceboots.com   Newspaper Web site: http://www.telegraph.co.uk   Newspaper Web site: http://www.express.co.uk   Newspaper Web site: http://www.observer.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 08:18 ET (12:18 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : BOS Announces $5 Million Rights Offering
Story: RISHON LE'ZION, Israel--(BUSINESS WIRE)--March 11, 2007--   B.O.S Better Online Solutions Ltd. (the "Company" or "BOS") (NASDAQ: BOSC; TASE: BOSC) announced that the registration statement previously filed by BOS with the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Israel Securities Authority, has been declared effective on March 8, 2007.     All of BOS's shareholders, who own shares as of 5:00 p.m., New York City time (midnight, Israel time) on March 19, 2007, the record date, will be entitled to participate in this offering, and receive one right for each 3.3724 ordinary shares owned of record on the record date. Each right will entitle the holder to purchase one ordinary share, at a subscription price of $2.50.     The rights will be exercisable during a 28-day period, beginning after 5:00 p.m., New York City time (midnight, Israel time) on March 20, 2007 and ending on April 16, 2007 at 5:00 p.m., New York City time (midnight, Israel time), or during a 23-day period, until April 11, 2007, for shareholders that hold the rights through an Israeli brokerage company that holds the rights through the Company's nominee company (Hevra Le-Rishumim of Bank leumi Le-Israel Ltd.)     The rights will be transferable and will be listed for trading for a single day, April 12, 2007, on the NASDAQ Global Market under the symbol "BOSCR" and on the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange under the symbol "BOSC.R1",.     The terms of the proposed rights distribution are described in the prospectus included in the registration statement. Copies of the prospectus can be obtained from the US Securities and Exchange Commission's EDGAR website at www.sec.gov and from the Israel Securities Authority's Magna website at www.magna.isa.gov.il. Copies of the prospectus may also be obtained from BOS's website at www.boscorporate.com or by contacting Mr. Eyal Cohen at 20 Freiman St. Rishon Le'Zion, Israel, telephone: 972-3-954-1000, or e-mail: eyalc@boscom.com.       About BOS     B.O.S Better Online Solutions Ltd. ("BOS") was established in 1990. Through its wholly owned subsidiaries, BOS's activities are focused on two segments:     Supply-Chain Solutions segment, based on Odem Electronic Technologies 1992 Ltd., providing solutions in the RFID, semiconductors, electronic components, CCD, imaging, networking, telecom and automation fields.     Software Solutions segment, with products marketed under the BOSaNOVA brand name. These products deliver instant and transparent connectivity from IBM iSeries computers to personal computers, thin clients and browsers.     BOS is traded on NASDAQ (BOSC) and on the Tel-Aviv Stock Exchange (BOSC). BOS's website address is www.boscorporate.com.     The forward-looking statements contained herein reflect management's current views with respect to future events and financial performance. These forward-looking statements are subject to certain risks and uncertainties that could cause the actual results to differ materially from those in the forward-looking statements, all of which are difficult to predict and many of which are beyond the control of BOS. These risk factors and uncertainties include, amongst others, the dependency of sales being generated from one or a few major customers, the uncertainty of our being able to maintain current gross profit margins, inability to keep up or ahead of technology and to succeed in a highly competitive industry, inability to maintain marketing and distribution arrangements and to expand our overseas markets, uncertainty with respect to the prospects of legal claims against BOS; and additional risks and uncertainties detailed in BOS's periodic reports and registration statements filed with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. BOS undertakes no obligation to publicly update or revise any such forward-looking statements to reflect any change in its expectations or in events, conditions or circumstances on which any such statements may be based, or that may affect the likelihood that actual results will differ from those set forth in the forward-looking statements.        CONTACT: B.O.S Better Online Solutions Ltd.               Mr. Gilad Friedhaber, +972-54-8110410               gilad@kwan.co.il               or               Mr. Eyal Cohen, CFO, +972-3-954-1000               eyalc@boscom.com        SOURCE: B.O.S Better Online Solutions Ltd. Headline: Citigroup's Announcement On Buy Of Taiwan Bk Postponed-Source
Story: TAIPEI (Dow Jones)--Citigroup Inc. (C) and Taiwan's Bank of Overseas Chinese (5818.OT) have postponed an announcement on an acquisition worth around NT$14 billion originally scheduled for Monday, a person familiar with the situation said late Sunday.   The postponement comes as New York Life Insurance Co. (NYI.XX) has requested to negotiate with Citigroup terms of a 10-year agreement it signed with the Taiwanese lender in 2005, the person said, who asked not to be named.   Under that agreement, New York Life bought a 4.5% stake in Bank of Overseas Chinese. In return, the bank will only sell insurance policies from New York Life.   The person wouldn't elaborate details of New York Life's request.   Citigroup and New York Life are expected to sort out the issue by Wednesday, the person added.   Citigroup's Taiwan manager Morris Li, Bank of Overseas Chinese Spokesman Weng Chien and New York Life officials were unavailable for comments late Sunday.   Because of the announcement's postponement, Bank of Overseas Chinese and Polaris Securities Co. (2854.TW) have postponed their board meetings originally slated for Monday, the person added.   Citigroup plans to pay around NT$14 billion to acquire all of Bank of Overseas Chinese in an all-cash deal, which values Bank of Overseas Chinese around NT$11.6-NT$11.8 per share.     -By Perris Lee Choon Siong, Dow Jones Newswires; 8862-2502-2557; perris.lee@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 11:09 ET (15:09 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: BMI Considering Legal Action On Open Skies - Newspaper
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--BMI British Midland Airways Ltd. is considering legal action if the U.K. government votes against the proposed 'open skies' deal between Europe and the U.S., The Observer newspaper reports Sunday.   It quoted Michael Bishop, BMI's chairman, saying BMI has considered its legal position, though "it is not something we are making much of at the moment."   The U.S. and European Union two weeks ago announced a draft deal to free up air travel across the Atlantic, allowing each other's airlines to fly from any city in Europe to any city in U.S. and vice versa.   The deal would particularly benefit BMI since it would be able to start services from London's Heathrow airport to U.S. cities currently controlled by four airlines - British Airways PLC (BAB), Virgin Atlantic, American Airlines (AMR) and United Airlines (UAL).   The U.K. hasn't said whether or not it will try to veto the deal but U.K. Transport Secretary Douglas Alexander this week said the deal "falls short" in its scope and more work needs to be done before it could be approved.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.observer.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 10:18 ET (14:18 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: WSJA(3/12) Bridging The Gap Between Here And There
Story: (From THE WALL STREET JOURNAL ASIA)     By Phred Dvorak   WHEN Ray O'Connor was hired as marketing director for the U.S. unit of Japan's Topcon Corp. in 1993, his friends predicted disaster.   Japanese companies were notoriously slow to trust local managers and reluctant to adopt their ideas. Topcon, a maker of surveying and medical equipment affiliated with Japan's Toshiba Corp., was so traditional that U.S. workers warned Mr. O'Connor not to go home without saying goodnight to the boss.   Fourteen years later, Mr. O'Connor is still at Topcon. He now runs Topcon's biggest U.S. unit, which accounts for roughly one-quarter of Topcon's global revenue and half its profit. Last year, Topcon put him in charge of much of its European and Australian businesses as well.   The secret to his success: perseverance and working with the home culture. Mr. O'Connor wooed managers and engineers in Japan. He spent nine months re-engineering an acquisition after his Japanese boss initially balked. He didn't lobby for promotions, working for two years under a manager sent from Tokyo, then another six years as co-president of the U.S. business before getting the full title.   "It was a step-by-step process," says the 44-year-old Mr. O'Connor. "Some people don't have the patience for that."   Mr. O'Connor's story shows how local managers for foreign companies often must adapt to succeed. They need to win the trust of distant bosses who may be out of touch with local markets. And they must strike a balance between effective local leadership and sensitivity to corporate custom.   That can be especially challenging for companies based in countries -- such as Japan or South Korea -- with strong unspoken business traditions, says Bruce McKern, a professor in international business at Stanford Graduate School of Business. "If the local manager isn't connected to the network of the company, it can be crippling," Mr. McKern says.   Consider Howard Stringer. The American-Welsh Sony Corp. executive won points with his Japanese bosses while running operations in the U.S., with deference to Tokyo customs and an easy-going attitude on pay and promotions. When he took over the CEO job in 2005, he moved carefully in Japan, waiting until late last year to gently shuffle top management.   Mr. McKern says local managers in foreign multinationals can help close the gap between themselves and headquarters by learning the language of the home country or spending time there. Any overseas experience can help managers understand how to navigate different cultures, he says.   Mr. O'Connor, an Irish civil engineer, joined Topcon after nine years at a U.S. maker of laser-guidance tools used on construction sites. At the time, Topcon's U.S. operation merely sold products made in Tokyo, and all of Topcon's overseas units were run by Japanese. But the company wanted to expand its optical-surveying tools into lasers and construction and hired Mr. O'Connor to help.   Mr. O'Connor quickly realized that he would need support from Japanese managers, and shuttled back and forth almost every month to pitch his ideas and explain the American market. He wooed product developers in Tokyo, letting them take credit for tweaks he'd suggested. He earned points early on when he refused to criticize Japanese engineers who couldn't make a prototype laser work for an important U.S. trade show.   "I was really moved by that," says Satoshi "Steve" Hirano, the manager in charge of the laser, now a deputy division chief. "I went back to Japan and told everyone that Ray could be trusted."   Mr. O'Connor's tactics paid off. In 1994, Mr. Hirano and another manager, Norio Uchida, backed Mr. O'Connor's plan to buy a California company that made software to automate control of construction equipment and invest heavily in developing new products.   Yukinari "Bob" Iguchi, the Japanese executive running Topcon's U.S. operations, was skeptical: Topcon had never done an acquisition that wasn't proposed by headquarters, and its engineers knew little about software. Mr. Iguchi balked, and Mr. O'Connor spent months persuading him to put the deal back together. When it was done, Mr. Uchida was assigned to run the acquired company. Mr. Iguchi says Japanese corporate custom didn't permit him to put a newcomer like Mr. O'Connor atop a unit.   Mr. O'Connor says he was happy to work under Mr. Uchida, and was more concerned about getting the new business started.   The new company lost money for four straight years. Messrs. Hirano and Uchida defended the business in Tokyo. Mr. Uchida says he was comforted because Mr. O'Connor always made his sales targets, and didn't complain about pay or push for a promotion -- even when Mr. Hirano was later sent from Tokyo to run the U.S. company as co-president. The unit began making money in 1998.   In 2000, Messrs. Hirano and Uchida backed Mr. O'Connor in another bid: a big, risky investment in a company that used satellites to determine an object's position. Mr. O'Connor wanted to use the technology to guide Topcon's surveying equipment, as well as construction machinery like bulldozers. But the $30 million price tag was more than Topcon had ever spent on an acquisition, and Topcon itself was losing money.   Again, Mr. Iguchi got cold feet, calling Mr. O'Connor to postpone negotiations the night before Mr. O'Connor was to leave for Tokyo. Mr. Iguchi says he wanted more time to persuade other board members to support the deal. Mr. O'Connor persuaded Mr. Iguchi to move ahead. Then the deal was nearly derailed by a breach of Japanese etiquette. Mr. O'Connor had given the CEO of the company Topcon was acquiring a $750 box of cigars.   Mr. Iguchi says he had intended to present the cigars himself, but that the incident "wasn't so serious." In the end, the deal remained so controversial internally that Topcon's then-CEO refused to sign the papers.   These days, Topcon's Japanese executives are themselves adapting, as Mr. O'Connor's unit -- and overseas markets -- grow in importance. In the fiscal year ended Mar. 31, 2006, 65% of Topcon's roughly $870 million in revenue came from outside of Japan, up from 53% five years earlier. Topcon Positioning Systems, the U.S. unit that Mr. O'Connor was named to run in 2002, accounted for about half of Topcon's roughly $58 million in annual net income.   Last year, Mr. O'Connor was put in charge of world-wide sales and marketing for the positioning division. Topcon CEO Takashi Yokokura says that Topcon's medical-equipment division is considering copying the positioning unit's techniques, such as a more aggressive acquisition strategy and global technology and marketing meetings. Managers in the medical division are saying, "'We want Ray O'Connor,'" Mr. Yokokura says.   Mr. Uchida, now a Topcon director, says that Topcon Positioning Systems' latest acquisition in September -- of an Australian maker of equipment-control software -- was approved by Topcon's board in record time: one hour.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 17:30 ET (21:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: China Chalco 2006 Net Profit CNY11.75B; Up 67% On Year
Story: HONG KONG (Dow Jones)--Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd. (ACH), the world's second-largest alumina producer by output after Alcoa Inc., said Sunday its 2006 net profit jumped 67%, boosted by higher output.   The Hong Kong-listed company, known as Chalco, posted a net profit of CNY11.75 billion for the year ended Dec. 31, 2006, up from CNY7.02 billion in 2005.   The result was in line with the average CNY11.5 billion forecast of 21 analysts polled by Thomson Financial.   Revenue last year rose to CNY61.90 billion from CNY37.83 billion.   Chalco, China's largest alumina and aluminum producer, produced 8.83 million metric tons of alumina in 2006, up 23% from 2005. Its primary aluminum output in 2006 rose 84% to 1.93 million tons.   Alumina is the raw material used to produce aluminum.     -By Joyce Li, Dow Jones Newswires; 852-2802-7002; joyce.li@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 05:24 ET (09:24 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : Precision Assessment Technology Corporation - Investment By Bison Capital Equity Partners>PDT.T
Story: VANCOUVER, March 9 /CNW/ - As previously announced on March 1, 2007, Precision Assessment Technology Corporation ("Precision" or the "Company") (TSX:PDT) has entered into a letter agreement with Bison Capital Equity Partners II, L.P., a private equity fund based in Los Angeles, California ("Bison"), with respect to a US$12 million equity investment in Precision.    The proceeds of the financing will be used to fund two acquisitions, to pay down existing debt and for general working capital and, when completed, will add to Precision's management depth. The financing is subject to fulfillment of various conditions, including formal documentation and receipt of approval of the Toronto Stock Exchange ("TSX").    The initial investment by Bison will involve the purchase by Bison of 8,000 shares of exchangeable preferred stock ("Preferred Stock") of a wholly-owned US subsidiary of Precision ("Precision US") for a subscription price of US$1,000 per share. The share provisions attaching to the Preferred Stock will contain certain restrictions, including restrictions on indebtedness, minimum EBITDA requirements, asset sales, acquisitions, capital expenditures and dividends. The Preferred Stock will bear a cumulative dividend of 10% per annum if paid in cash or common shares of Precision ("PATC Shares") and 12% per annum in the event such dividends accumulate and are not paid (subject to adjustment in the event Precision US is in default of certain covenants), and holders will be entitled to receive an extraordinary dividend on the fifth anniversary (the amount of which shall be dependent upon the number of shares of Preferred Stock redeemed by Precision US prior to the fifth anniversary). Any Preferred Stock not redeemed by Precision US by the fifth anniversary date will be exchanged by the holder for PATC Shares on the basis of 4,348 PATC Shares for each one share of Preferred Stock (the "Exchange Ratio"), subject to adjustment prior to closing based on financial statements for the year ended December 31, 2006, with any accrued and unpaid dividends paid in cash at the time of exchange. The Exchange Ratio is also subject to standard anti-dilution provisions. The initial investment may result in the issue of up to 34,784,000 PATC Shares. Precision US has the right to repurchase up to 4,000 shares of Preferred Stock ("Clean-up Right"), which, if exercised, will reduce the number of PATC Shares issuable to 17,392,000.    The second investment by Bison will consist of the purchase by Bison of up to 21,703,743 PATC Shares, subject to adjustment prior to closing based on financial statements for the year ended December 31, 2006, for a purchase price of approximately C$0.22 (US$.1843) per PATC Share for aggregate subscription proceeds of US$4,000,000.    The completion of each of the initial investment by Bison is subject to numerous conditions, including the concurrent completion of the proposed acquisition of BC2 Environmental Corp., a southern California drilling company, and the second investment is subject to the condition that either the eastern United States drilling services company referenced in Precision's March 1, 2007 news release (or an alternative) be completed. The proposed acquisitions also contemplate, subject to regulatory approval, the issuance of up to 4,006,500 PATC Shares as partial purchase price and, if applicable, earn-out consideration. The equity financing and the acquisitions are also subject to receipt of all required regulatory approvals, including approval by the TSX.    Precision currently has 77,446,107 PATC Shares issued and outstanding on a non-diluted basis (83,406,614 on a fully diluted basis). If the Clean-up Right is exercised, the equity financing and the acquisitions may result in the issue of up to an additional 43,102,243 PATC Shares (representing 34.3% of the issued and outstanding shares following the equity financing and the acquisitions, or 55.6% of the current issued and outstanding). If all of the Preferred Stock is exchanged into PATC Shares, the equity financing and the acquisitions may result in the issue of up to an additional 60,494,243 PATC Shares (representing 43.8% of the issued and outstanding shares following the equity financing and the acquisitions, or 78.1% of the current issued and outstanding).    The equity financing will result in a new holding of more than 20% of the issued and outstanding PATC Shares by one security holder, which may be considered by the TSX to materially affect control. If all of the Preferred Stock is exchanged into PATC Shares, Bison will hold up to 56,487,743 PATC Shares (representing 42.1% of the issued and outstanding shares on a post-conversion basis). Currently, Conor Pacific Canada Inc. owns, or exercises control or direction over, 24,781,567 PATC Shares (representing 32% of the current issued and outstanding). Assuming all of the Preferred Stock is exchanged into PATC Shares by Bison, Conor Pacific's interest in Precision will be reduced to 18%.    No insider of the Company has any direct or indirect interest in the equity financing or the acquisitions, and all of the parties thereto are dealing at arm's length.    Shareholder approval of the equity financing and the acquisitions is required by the TSX. Precision is relying on section 604(d) of the TSX Company Manual, which permits the Company to provide the TSX with written evidence that holders of more than 50% of the PATC Shares are familiar with the terms of, and are in favour of, the equity financing and the acquisitions, in lieu of holding a shareholders meeting. The acquisitions and the first and second investments under the equity financing anticipated to close on or about March 15, 2007.    About Precision - Precision provides drilling services for site assessment and remediation and groundwater assessment, monitoring and mitigation in the United States. These services are provided using specialized and innovative drilling and sampling equipment and technologies from offices in California and Florida. Precision Assessment Technology Corporation operates through its wholly owned U.S. subsidiaries, Precision Sampling, Inc. and Trenchless Specialties Inc. Further information can be found at www.precisiontecha.com. Precision's common shares are listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange under the symbol "PDT". Headline: BG Group Could Be On Verge Of Investing In Iraq - Newspaper
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--BG Group PLC (BGG) could become the first major Western energy company to invest in Iraq, the Sunday Telegraph reports, without citing sources.   The paper says representatives from BG recently visited the northern region of Iraq in a move to assess the opportunities.   BG is believed to be interested in any opportunities for gas exploration; the Kurdish-controlled north, which has escaped much of the violence of the south, is home to about a fifth of Iraq's total reserves.   BG told the paper it "is looking at a number of opportunities across the Middle East."   Newspaper Web site: http://www.telegraph.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9330     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 07:00 ET (11:00 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--The U.K. Government intervened to help U.K. and U.S. energy giants in their attempts to secure lucrative contracts to exploit Iraq's ruined oilfields, The Independent on Sunday reports, citing a study by Washington-based think-tank the International Tax and Investment Center.   The study recommended the Iraqi government sign long-term production-sharing agreements with foreign oil companies, including Royal Dutch Shell PLC (RDSB) and BP PLC (BP).   Emails between civil servants also showed the Foreign Office helped the ITIC secure an audience with senior officials from the Iraqi Oil Ministry so it could present its report.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.independent.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9330     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 07:20 ET (11:20 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Volkswagen To Pay 10% Of Oper Profit To Staff In 2007 -Report
Story: FRANKFURT (Dow Jones)--German car maker Volkswagen AG (VLKAY) will pay premiums of 10% of its operating profit to its employees in 2007, German newspaper Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung writes Sunday, citing VW Executive Board Member responsible for human resources, Horst Neumann.   Volkswagen will pay its 94,000 staff a premium of more than EUR2,200, Neumann told the paper.   "In the coming years, the amount will increase with improved results," Neumann says in the interview.   The company will also hire a higher number of university graduates in 2007 than in recent years, the paper quotes Neumann as saying.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.faz.de     -Frankfurt Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 49-69-29725-500.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 09:39 ET (13:39 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Prudential To Cut Jobs, UK Ops In Restructuring - Newspaper
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Prudential PLC (PRU.LN) will set out a series of restructuring proposals when it releases full-year results Thursday, the Sunday Times reports, including potentially cutting up 3,000 U.K. jobs and freeing up GBP9 billion in 'orphan' assets.   The newspaper says the insurer and financial services group will also announce plans to withdraw from unprofitable U.K. activities such as selling individual pensions and unit-linked bonds.   Prudential is likely to say it can make huge savings by outsourcing back-office jobs in its U.K. operation to its Mumbai unit, the Sunday Times says. It adds the company will also take steps to free up orphan, or inherited, estates that have been built up over decades and redeploy its share of the capital to finance growth opportunities.   A Prudential spokesman said he couldn't comment on speculation but said the firm has committed to report on the review of its U.K. business by March 15.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 08:59 ET (12:59 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UPDATE:China Chalco '06 Net +67%;Alumina Prices To Fluctuate
Story: (Updates with company statement, more details.)     By Joyce Li   of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     HONG KONG (Dow Jones)--Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd. (ACH), which posted Sunday a 67% jump in 2006 net profit on higher output, said the company will continue to expand its aluminum operations as it expects to see alumina prices to fluctuate on rising capacity in the market.   The company, better known as Chalco, posted a net profit of 11.75 billion yuan ($1.52 billion) for the year ended Dec. 31, 2006, up from CNY7.02 billion in 2005.   The result was in line with the average CNY11.5 billion forecast of 21 analysts polled by Thomson Financial.   Earnings growth was helped by rising output of both alumina and aluminum. The company produced alumina of 8.83 million metric tons in 2006, up 23% on year. Production of primary aluminum grew 84% to 1.93 million tons.   Alumina is the raw material to produce aluminum.   Prior to the earnings result, analysts had said expected higher profits would be helped by an increase in output and strong selling prices of both alumina and aluminum.   Despite weaker alumina prices in the second half of last year, Daiwa Institutes of Research said it expected Chalco's 2006 earnings would benefit from strong alumina prices for a large part of the year, translating to an annual average selling price of about CNY3,663 a ton, up 12.1% on year.   Chalco didn't provide average selling prices of any products in its statement.   Xiao Yaqing, Chalco's chief executive, said the company recorded stable growth in production and profit in 2006. But the outlook for company's alumina operations is likely to be rough.   "In future, Chalco will face a series of challenges, such as product price fluctuation, rising price of major raw and ancillary materials and intensifying market competition arising from rapidly expanding production capacity of alumina," Xiao said in a statement.   "The high economic growth of the world and China are expected to persist, which will drive the growth of aluminum consumption and bring more room for development of the group," he added.   In 2007, Chalco will consolidate, merge and acquire suitable aluminum enterprises to expand its production capacity. It will also list its A shares while seeking new financing channels to meet development needs, the company said in the statement.   "Chalco will accelerate the construction of key projects, focus on acquisition of resources and control," the company said.   Chalco has been expanding its downstream aluminum operations to mitigate the effect of intensifying competition in the alumina business due to a rising number of new entrants.   Chalco slashed the spot price of its alumina four times, or a total of 58%, between August and November because of higher domestic production. Before the price cuts, Chalco had been selling alumina at a spot price of as high as CNY5,650 a ton.   Early last month, Chalco raised the spot price of its alumina 50% to CNY3,600 a ton to match the higher prices of its rivals.   Chalco, the world's second-largest alumina producer by output after U.S.-based Alcoa Inc., said revenue last year rose to CNY61.90 billion from CNY37.83 billion.   Chalco, which is China's largest alumina and aluminum producer, said it will declare final dividend, translating into distributable profit of about CNY1.48 billion, after the completion of its share-swap plan and A-share listing.   Chalco received shareholder approval in February to offer CNY8.2 billion worth of its shares to swap with the remaining shares it doesn't own in unit Shandong Aluminum Industry Co. (600205.SH) and affiliate Lanzhou Aluminum Co. Ltd (600296.SH).   Under the plan, Chalco will issue 604.8 million of its new A shares to holders of Shandong Aluminum tradable shares. It will also issue 631.93 million of its new A shares to other shareholders in Lanzhou Aluminium.     -By Joyce Li, Dow Jones Newswires; 852-2802-7002; joyce.li@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 06:24 ET (10:24 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Siemens Also Mulling Sale Of VDO Unit - Report
Story: FRANKFURT (Dow Jones)--German technology conglomerate Siemens AG (SI) is also preparing for a sale of its VDO unit, the Financial Times Deutschland reported in an advance release of an article to be published Monday, citing financial industry sources.   Siemens has hired the investment bank Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (GS) in case the company sells VDO, a supplier of automotive electronics, rather than float a part of the unit as currently planned by management, according to the FT Deutschland.   In the coming weeks, Siemens' IPO adviser Lazard Ltd. (LAZ) will chose a bank that will carry out the potential VDO flotation, the paper also reported.     Newspaper Web site: http://www.ftd.de     -Frankfurt Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 49-69-29725-500.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 13:31 ET (17:31 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Israel's Bank Hapoalim To Sell 25% Of Unit To Phoenix Hldgs
Story: JERUSALEM (Dow Jones)--Israel's Bank Hapoalim B.M. (POLI.TV) has agreed to sell 25% of its credit card unit to The Phoenix Holdings Ltd. (PHOE1.TV), Hapoalim said Sunday in a statement to the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange.   The price that Phoenix will pay will be based on a company value of 2.55 billion shekels ($607 million), the statement said.   Bank Hapoalim expects to report at least ILS255 million in net profit from the sale. At 0930 GMT, Poalim's shares were up 1.04% at ILS19.50 and Phoenix's shares were up 2.72% at ILS20.40 on a higher Tel Aviv market.   Phoenix is an Israel-based holding company with interests mainly in finance and insurance. Bank Hapoalim is Israel's biggest bank by sector share, with about 40% of the sector.   -By Sara Toth, Contributing to Dow Jones Newswires, saratoth@yahoo.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 05:37 ET (09:37 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Israel's Discount Bank Raises ILS350 Million From Bond Sale
Story: JERUSALEM (Dow Jones)--Israel Discount Bank Ltd. (DSCT.TV) has raised 350 million shekels ($83 million) from the sale of bonds, the bank said Sunday in a statement to the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange.   The bank raised ILS315 million from bonds sold to institutional investors, and ILS35 million from bonds sold to the public, the statement said. The bonds are for eight years, maturing in 2015, the statement said, and will pay interest of 6.1%.   The bonds have been rated AA by Maalot, the Israeli rating agency, the statement said. Discount's shares were up 0.29% at ILS9.55 on a higher Tel Aviv market at 945 GMT.   By Sara Toth, Contributing to Dow Jones Newswires, saratoth@yahoo.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 06:27 ET (10:27 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: BP Set To Receive More Criticism Over Texas City
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--BP PLC (BP) is likely to face more criticism from a U.S. agency over the fatal explosion at its Texas City refinery in 2005, reports the U.K.'s Observer newspaper.   On Mar. 20, the U.S. Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board's report will likely cite evidence showing BP's management prioritized budgetary concerns over investment in safety.   "We make the link between cost-cutting and the event that occurred on 23 March 2005," The Observer reports, citing CSB chairman Carolyn Merritt.   The CSB report follows a first report by former U.S. Secretary of State James Baker, who heavily criticized BP management for a "systemic" lack of leadership on safety.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.observer.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9330     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 08:27 ET (12:27 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Germany's RWE To Merge 4 Gas Market Areas >RWEOY
Story: FRANKFURT (Dow Jones)--German utility RWE AG (RWEOY) said it will merge its four German gas market areas into two as of Apr. 1.   RWE will then have one market area for high-caloric natural gas, or H-gas, and one for low-caloric natural gas, or L-gas. H-gas has a higher share of methane than L-gas.   Reducing the number of market areas will create more liquid trading hubs, RWE said, and promote competition among gas transportation companies.   Company Web site: http://www.rwe.com     -By Frankfurt Bureau; Dow Jones Newswires; +49 69 29 725 500; djnews.frankfurt@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 12:32 ET (16:32 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: =WSJ: Ford Near Deal To Sell Aston Martin
Story: (This story and related background material will be available on The Wall Street Journal Web site, WSJ.com.)       By Stephen Power and Jason Singer     Of THE WALL STREET JOURNAL     (Dow Jones) Ford Motor Co. (F) is nearing a deal to sell its Aston Martin brand, in what would mark the end of a six-month effort to unload the unit and free up cash at a time when the company's North American business is struggling.   Ford is likely to announce Monday the sale of its Aston Martin sports car division to an investor group led by international motor racing entrepreneur David Richards in a deal that values the brand at about GBP450 million, according to people familiar with the situation.   Ford, which is selling the iconic British sports car maker to free its resources to invest more in its core brands, will retain a 15% stake in the company, these people added. Richards is backed by Kuwait's Investment Dar, a holding company, among others. Richards is also chairman of Prodrive Ltd., an auto racing firm, but Prodrive isn't participating in the purchase, these people added.   A spokesman for Prodrive, Ben Sayer, declined to comment Friday on whether the company was in talks to purchase Aston Martin from Ford.   Aston Martin, the British brand most famous for its association with the James Bond films, is grouped with Jaguar, Land Rover and Volvo in Premier Automotive Group, a collection of upscale European nameplates that Ford once predicted would generate nearly a third of its operating profit by the middle of this decade. PAG, however, has reported massive losses in recent years, including a $1.6 billion loss in 2005, mainly as a result of losses by Jaguar. Some analysts say a sale of Aston Martin could allow Ford to better reposition Jaguar as more of an up-market niche brand.   Disposing of Aston Martin would pare down PAG's losses and raise cash to fund a restructuring of Ford's loss-plagued North American operations. It would also amount to a scaling back of Ford's effort to turn PAG into a major player in luxury automobiles with the scale of upscale car makers such as BMW AG and DaimlerChrysler AG's Mercedes-Benz division.   Ford had hoped to use PAG to cash in on the boom in luxury-car sales over the past 10 years. But the strategy has been complicated by troubles at Jaguar, which has continued posting losses in the hundreds of millions of dollars despite several restructuring efforts and the addition of a small sedan that was supposed to lure younger customers.     -By Stephen Power and Jason Singer, The Wall Street Journal     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 09:40 ET (13:40 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : Luxell Reports Results For Fiscal 2006>LUX.T
Story: TORONTO, March 9 /CNW/ - Luxell Technologies Inc. (TSX:LUX) today announced results for fiscal 2006. The Company reported that revenues for the year ending August 31, 2006 were $3,328,352, as compared with $2,800,601 for the prior fiscal year. The total net loss for 2006 was $8,775,586 or $0.20 per share compared to a net loss of $7,169,442 or $0.17 per share for 2005.    Revenues for the fourth quarter ended August 31, 2006 were $838,000 compared to $1,003,455 for the same period in 2005. The net loss for the fourth quarter ended August 31, 2006 was $3,237,000 versus a loss of $1,801,535 for the fourth quarter of 2005.    On August 28, 2006, just prior to the end of the 4th quarter and year end, Luxell filed a Notice of Intent to make a proposal (the "Proposal") to its creditors under the Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act (Canada). BDO Dunwoody were appointed as Trustee. On October 18, 2006, the majority of the Company's creditors voted in favour of a submitted proposal and this was subsequently approved by the Superior Court of Justice on November 7, 2006.    John MacDonald, Chairman and Luxell's interim-CEO at the 2006 year-end said, "I'm confident that as the current year unfolds, shareholders will begin to see a completely new company emerge. The Board of Directors is extremely pleased to see what our new management group is achieving as they continue to restructure sales and operations and move Luxell towards profitability. I hope we see a lot of shareholders come out for the AGM where they will be able to meet the new management team and get more information on the positive changes taking place."    For more details please see the complete filings posted on the Sedar web site.    About Luxell    Luxell designs, manufactures and licenses flat panel display technologies and solutions for defence and avionics industries. More information can be found at www.luxell.com. (C) Luxell Technologies Inc., Luxell and Black Layer are trademarks of Luxell Technologies Inc. All other company and/or product names are trademarks and/or registered trademarks of their respective manufacturers.    %SEDAR: 00008266E         /CONTACT: Luxell Technologies Inc.: Simon Dann, Director, Corporate Communications & Investor Relations, (905) 363-0325, sdann@luxell.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 10:11 ET (14:11 GMT)

Headline: UK Cos Could Bid For Spain's Continental Autos - Newspaper
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Two U.K. transport companies are considering bids for Spanish bus operator Continental Auto, which is owned by Actividades de Construccion y Servicios SA (ACS.MC), The Sunday Times reports without citing sources.   National Express Group PLC (NEX.LN) and Arriva PLC (ARI.LN) are said to be studying the Spanish company's financial information, the newspaper says. The unit is expected to fetch around EUR600 million.   An Arriva spokeswoman declined to comment and National Express wasn't immediately available to comment.   Continental Auto runs about 60 bus routes in Spain and has subsidiaries in freight, hotels, catering and rail operations. Actividades de Construccion y Servicios is Spain's largest construction company by market capitalization.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 10:40 ET (14:40 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: ABN To Appease Investors With Dividend, Disposals - Newspaper
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--ABN Amro Holding NV (ABN) is to promise to pay a special dividend and make minor disposals at its annual general meeting next month to appease hedge funds that have demanded a break-up or sale of the bank, the Sunday Telegraph reports.   The newspaper, citing people close to the bank, says ABN will put "almost all" five proposals made by U.K. hedge fund the Children's Investment Fund, or TCI, on the agenda at its April 26 AGM.   ABN wasn't immediately available to comment.   TCI last month called for shareholder votes on pursuing sales, spin-offs or mergers of ABN units, to have cash returned to shareholders of any disposals through share buybacks or special dividends, to investigate selling or merging the entire company, to cease acquisitions for six months from the AGM, and to have ABN report to shareholders on the outcome of these activites within six months of the AGM.   Several other shareholders have said they broadly support the proposals, including Dutch pension fund PGGM and Toscafund Asset Management LLP, another U.K. hedge-fund group.   The Sunday Telegraph, citing a person close to ABN, says adding more debt to the bank's balance sheet would be an "affordable" way to fund a payout to shareholders.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.telegraph.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 08:42 ET (12:42 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: NZX Puts Promina On Trading Halt Ahead Of Suncorp Merger Vote
Story: WELLINGTON (Dow Jones)--Promina Group Ltd.'s (PMN.AU) New Zealand listed shares have been placed on trading halt ahead of a special meeting to approve a proposed merger with Suncorp-Metway Ltd. (SUN.AU), exchange operator New Zealand Exchange Ltd. (NZX.NZ) said Monday.   The exchange operator said in a statement that the trading halt is effective from the start of business Monday, in accordance with the timetable of the proposed Scheme of Arrangement.   Details for delisting Promina will be provided in "due course," the New Zealand Exchange said.     -By Wellington Bureau; 64-4-471-5990; djnews.wellington@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 17:21 ET (21:21 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Agricultural Bank Of China Audit Unlikely In 1H-China Auditor
Story: BEIJING (Dow Jones)--China's top auditor said Sunday he doesn't expect the National Audit Office's audit of Agricultural Bank of China can be completed in the first half of this year.   But the office's audit of the bank isn't a necessary step in its stockholding restructuring, Li Jinhua, auditor-general of the National Audit Office, added on the sidelines of the National People's Congress, the country's legislature.   At the beginning of February, Agricultural Bank of China Vice President Han Zhongqi said a concrete value for any sort of government recapitalization of the bank could only be decided after external auditor Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu International and the National Audit Office had delivered audits of the lender.   Agricultural Bank of China is the weakest of China's Big Four state banks and the only one yet to complete a financial restructuring and listing.   As part of the restructuring of the other three Big Four banks - Industrial & Commercial Bank of China Ltd., Bank of China Ltd. and China Construction Bank Corp. - the government recapitalized them with fund injections ahead of their listings.   Agricultural Bank of China hopes to complete its financial restructuring in the second half of this year, Han said in early February.     -Victoria Ruan contributed to this story, Dow Jones Newswires; 8601 6588-5848; victoria.ruan@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 05:31 ET (09:31 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: =WSJ: Head Of Volkswagen's Bugatti Unit Stepping Down
Story: (This story and related background material will be available on The Wall Street Journal Web site, WSJ.com.)       By Stephen Power     Of THE WALL STREET JOURNAL     (Dow Jones)--The head of Volkswagen AG's (VLKAY) luxury Bugatti sports-car unit is stepping down, becoming the latest high-level executive to quit his post following the resignation of CEO Bernd Pischetsrieder late last year.   A spokesman for Bugatti said Sunday that its president, Thomas Bscher, had submitted his letter of resignation within the past few days, confirming a report in the German magazine Der Spiegel that Bscher intended to leave his post.   Bscher's resignation comes two months after the resignation of Wolfgang Bernhard. Bernhard - a former member of Volkswagen AG's management board with responsibility for its core Volkswagen brand - left the auto maker at the end of January.    "He's done a good job," the Bugatti spokesman, Georges Keller said of Bscher. "He took the [Bugatti] project over when it was in trouble, and he took the whole thing on and put the car on the road. It's like in football. If you're going to retire, you want to do so when you're on top."    With a top speed of 407 kilometers per hour and a price tag of around EUR1 million, Bugatti's Veyron sports car has been a difficult project for Volkswagen management. Championed by Volkswagen's chairman, Ferdinand Piech, the car's development was plagued for years by technical problems and cost overruns, prompting Pischetsrieder - who succeeded Mr. Piech as Volkswagen CEO in 2002 - to recruit Bscher, a former Formula 1 race-car driver, to take charge of the project in 2003.        Although Bugatti has begun delivering Veyrons to customers, its future product plans are unclear. At the North American International Auto Show in January, Porsche AG CEO Wendelin Wiedeking told reporters that Volkswagen should not subsidize any "toys." Wiedeking is a member of Volkswagen's supervisory board, and his company is Volkswagen's largest shareholder.      "One rule we have to follow in the future is that every product has to make money," Wiedeking said.      Bscher could not be reached for comment Sunday.     -By Stephen Power, The Wall Street Journal     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 10:08 ET (14:08 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Chinese Lawmaker Urges Removing Starbucks From Forbidden City
Story: BEIJING (AP)--A Chinese lawmaker revived calls for the removal of a Starbucks (SBUX) coffee shop from Beijing's famed Forbidden City, saying its presence was a smear on China's historical legacy, the official Xinhua News Agency reported Sunday.   Jiang Hongbin, a deputy from the northeastern province of Heilongjiang, said he submitted a motion to the National People's Congress, the country's legislature, to close the outlet immediately, Xinhua said.   Starbucks "can no longer be allowed to taint China's national culture," Jiang was quoted as saying.   The outlet has stirred controversy among Chinese nationalists ever since it opened in 2000 in a side hall of the 587-year-old former home of China's Ming and Qing dynasty emperors, now a museum visited by 7 million people each year.   Calls for it to close grew again in January when a television host launched an online campaign to toss it out. Museum managers and the government haven't responded publicly to the demands.   It wasn't clear whether Jiang's motion would be discussed by the nearly 3,000-member congress, which meets in full session only once a year and is widely regarded as a rubber stamp for policies decided by the government.   Defenders say the Starbucks is popular with tourists and its rent helps pay for the upkeep of the sprawling vermillion-walled, 178-acre complex of villas and gardens, now undergoing a thorough renovation ahead of the 2008 Beijing Olympic Summer Games.   However, Jiang said the integrity of Chinese culture should take precedence over funding concerns.   "The Forbidden City is one of the non-tradable products as its value cannot be measured with money," Jiang said. "As long as it (Starbucks) stays in the imperial palace, it poses a challenge to our traditional culture."     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 11, 2007 01:57 ET (06:57 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.
